What's the story? ČSSD in Prague doesn't know Voldemort or the pastry shop
The new ČSSD councillors in the capital are reportedly going to have to overcome the obvious language barriers in order for the members of the Prague Board and the City Council to understand their renewed colleagues in the SDG.
The Aktuálně.cz period "examined" the members of the new ČSSD Council to check their knowledge of the slang language that has emerged in recent years in the Council, when the current members of the coalition ruled Prague.
The coded dictionary that used Prague's political flower and cream during the previous period, by Mayor Pavel Bém, includes some of the best-known characters, situations and causes of the metropolis.
Surprisingly, it has been found that the new councillors almost do not understand these well-known concepts.
At least, that's what they say.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"The truth is, I don't know."
"I'm more of a novice in Prague politics," said Lukáš Kaucký, a culture councillor, during the "collegeo" terminology exam.
And as far as the political veteran is concerned, Karel Březina reacted as well.
Maybe they know the concept of golf today.
"Perhaps it's the only expression of all you've asked me what I use from time to time."
"If not, I usually don't use slang."
From the glossary, whose definitions published the Aktuálně.cz newspaper last June before the SDG voting congress, the wording selected six examples, in particular those that are particularly related to the municipal authorities of Prague.
Socialists had to explain the concepts "Voldemort", "larger golf hole of Prague", "go to the pastry shop", "nucky bull", "treasure of the capital" and "bridging".
Three councillors agreed to take the test and a fourth, Antonín Weinert, who in the future will be responsible for education in Prague, initially agreed, but did not pick up the phone again.
The fifth councillor, Petr Dolinek, refused directly to do so.
"I don't get involved in these things, and I don't think I'm going to appreciate how the democrats enjoy themselves."
"What I do care about is how we will understand each other in the implementation of our programs," he said.
As has been seen, councilman Lukáš Kaucký allegedly did not realize that the previous title is an expression about an influential businessman and a friend of former mayor Bem, Roman Janoušek.
To Kaucký the word "Voldemort" does not say anything; the only term that was correct in the exam is "the largest golf hole in Prague".
"It's about the Blanka tunnel," says Kaucký, who immediately adds: "But I know more about the news."
"I'm going to have to aim for a language course," he jokes.
Karel Březina is not the only one who recognizes the Blanka tunnel in the golf hole, but also Environment Councillor Lukáš Plachý.
Later, both socio-democrats know who Voldemort and Lukáš Plachý really are, even knows where to find that character; moreover, he suspects the meaning of "going to the pastry shop".
"I think it means going to a company in Prague"; it soon reveals to Plachý that it is the headquarters of the companies in Janoušek.
Like Březina, he indicates that such knowledge obtained from the news, but that he does not use such vocabulary.
According to the participants in the test, there is no such familiar glossary of colloquial terms among the socio-democrats.
"I asked my colleagues, but it really seems like we have nothing like it."
"Moreover, among us we use nicknames, sometimes abbreviations or we play word games with names," says ČSSD President Petr Hulinský, whose party mates call Hulda.
"At school I was called Bříza, but I don't know if my classmates also call me that," confesses his own nickname Karel Březina.
The Aktuálně.cz newspaper tested the name and works.
For his partymates, Weinert is Děda (similar to "yayo") or, less friendly, Dědek ("old"), the representative Miroslav Poche, with whom they were associated before the election deceptions during the party's sponsorship, receives the nickname "Igráček" ("playmobil") from some of his teammates.
The nicknames are also the only expressions that socio-democrats tolerate in speech within the party.
Hulinský doesn't like to be called Hulda, but the Aktuálně.cz newspaper even discovered other nicknames for this president.
"The Doctor of the Rights of Scum" apparently recalls that Petr Hulinský obtained his PhD in Law at the Bratislava police academy.
The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", as published in a brochure
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They tend to be of old age, cannot work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "return" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men rarely suffer such an ordeal."
"It also does not isolate healthy young women, because they help in the work and have children," explains a nun who, in the capital of the state of West Africa Burkina Faso, is working in a special residence of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an information leaflet that should help prevent witch hunting.
However, this has a stick.
"More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso can't read," the newspaper Die Standard warns about the disadvantages of written awareness.
The allegations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, a neighbouring country of Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week, when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared in the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to a wretched cluster of circumstances.
According to his version, the woman was stuck in the oil that is used for ritual anointings.
He set himself on fire when the group wanted to "expulsion the evil spirits" of the woman.
The isolation of the "witches" supports it people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: "Human soul eaters have always been a danger," he said.
While in Burkina Faso the Government was trying to appease witch-hunting, in the Gambia last year the President had still participated.
"Gambian President Jammeh, after his aunt's death, launched a wide hunt for witches who, supposedly, had been related to his death and had tried to kill the president himself by black magic."
"To help him, he brought in shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the personal escort of the president, were forcibly taken men and women randomly chosen from the Gambian peoples to the property of the president in Kanilai," says Amnesty International in his report.
On the farm, the arrested persons had to drink a pocima of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested did not survive their stay at the farm.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand people in detention.
Bakala's tenant: warms up with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The man, old and old, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal magnate" Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he was carrying documents with the new three-story rental contracts: his, his daughter's and his son's, who is serving the sentence.
The three of them just caught the rental liberalization.
Instead of 3,500 Czech kroner per month, the child will pay from next year 4,100 kroner for a two-room apartment with separate second category kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler", shows the man with his finger in his son's new contract, over whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," he explains, half angry, half resigned.
BytyOKD.cz civil association, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants not sign the new contracts and wait until 7 December, when they will publish a guide informing how to proceed in these cases.
But in the face of this, the man only makes a stick.
"Everything says one thing," he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a large laboratory of tests of liberalization.
After New Year's Eve it will happen with the vast majority of the floors that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
That is why Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
RPG's mining waiting room is one of the four of Ostrava's and, on Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a machine to take number.
"Rental 2011", can be read on a bright button on your touch screen.
When you press it, a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
Almost no time to read "157" and already the number appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an elderly marriage arrives to ask, but the crowd of the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, like in the past: settlement requests, insurance issues, and similar issues.
The letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the boxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 floors belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the letters a rent increase of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18 a special window is opened in the customer service center for new rentals.
"It's been running for a week, so it's starting," the workers who are in it when the client presents themselves as a journalist respond, after briefly doubting.
Liberalization and the former Bakala mining floors are the most delicate issues in the area.
Before the elections, the Vice-President of Parliament, from Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek of ČSSD, treated them loud and clear, and now appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
"I didn't even get changed by the goddamn bathroom," the man mentioned in the introduction unburdens himself.
According to the workers, for the moment they come more than just retired to check if they receive a rent discount if they sign on time, as the special offer of RPG promises.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before 15 December will also receive half of the rent discount for February.
However, the window of the mining "liberalization" certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked about the rent in 2011 about forty or fifty people," estimates the window employee.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach agreement on the rent, an independent judge will have to resolve the matter.
"It's not a threat, it's information about the only way to proceed in accordance with the law," RPG warns on his pages.
"No one is going to be judged here," says one of RPG Byty's employees and a man on the street in front of the customer service centre gives her, at least in part, the reason.
"I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for the food; I have no means to go to court," he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see about that."
"Mr. Zaoralek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait," he says.
Rental regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic in early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
"Current rents still do not cover even the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund," recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the housing portfolio of the RPG Byty company, who adds that the careless state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for the owners, the main reason to increase the rent.
While during the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest in four billion apartments with rents, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014, the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data that stand out in red.
"The rent increase in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG's properties."
"In addition, it will always be no more than 7.50 Czech crowns per square metre per month", it is indicated on the screen.
Just increase by 38% the rent of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
"In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts, of 19.66 crowns per square metre," says RPG.
On 2,600 floors, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalisation will not suddenly affect rents, but will climb between four and eight years.
In addition, he adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent rise (see the chart) back on the floors, mainly in heating savings: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the rent-up agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need day care
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would say that he also hides inside a small nursery with all the same to such installations: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outside terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of Arch.Design's employees can come to her.
Arch.Design architectural project company, from whose studio numerous known buildings came out of Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guard.
Around 90 people work in the company, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after motherhood.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, day care is one of the benefits Arch.Design offers to its workers as part of its social program.
Builders and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of their children.
The mini-guard was an idea of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-guard is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment, as well as the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (a budget of over CZK 2.8 million) they were able to buy the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified personnel and services.
When it exhausts the financing (two years), Arch.Design has an obligation to keep the miniguardry running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and in the submission of the application for funding contributed the company Economy Rating.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified staff, and a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care; the day-care centre currently accommodates children with no age limit, although most of them are under three years of age.
Since it is a "ministry", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible in order to adapt to the needs of the parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the enterprise.
Although it is an individual education and care, the contents of the mini-custodial programme are comparable to the regular preschool programme.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality education: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach to English.
The class has not only toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is placed among the companies they sign that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened staff marketing.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Observe Gaudí's interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the innovative use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade that recalls the scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, there is a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought out order.
At night, the whole facade of the house seems even more impressive, since it is illuminated so that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Snake and torsion of forms continues to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the railings, the ornaments of the doors, the mirrors and the signs.
Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gracia, arose from the remodeling of a house in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the rich industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, did not design it alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his plans of the project came ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the facade.
In the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Casa Milá and Gaudí's Güell Park, where other pieces of the same are found.
Due to its organic form, the locals soon after its completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific opening mechanism of the windows, began to call it "the house of the yawns".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Its inclination of forty-five degrees may be odd.
During the construction, Gaudí did not comply at all with the current construction rules and was not allowed to be influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although clearly in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so impacted by the result it asked for to be corrected.
He was disturbed, for example, by the fact that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather on the contrary: just fifteen days after the city council's request, Josep Batlló applied for (and obtained) permission to rent the two upper floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor there was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented from a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted in breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the lounges and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, gained not only a new façade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with the two colors brings the maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that the white reflects more light than the dark colors, which instead absorb the sun's rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and expanded the visits to the common area and the buhardilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of admission to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and tour card holders get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entry of other Gaudí constructions into the city.
