The era of viscoelastics with an open cell structure and a high density began with the "cosmic" material of Tempur.
It initially emerged as a material for NASA, because during the take-off the astronauts were subjected to a huge overload.
Tempur softens with heat and hardens with cold.
Therefore, the warm human body exerts a perfect effect and adapts its pressure optimally.
It is therefore ideal to prevent sores, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
Viscoelastic foam is used not only in mattresses, but also for sanitary devices, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
National manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and similar.
More and more parents use tracking devices to control their children
Fear of children increasingly leads more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old girl Anička Janatková.
At the moment the device is about the size of a matchbox, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were afraid of the case of the missing Anička and began to report on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the expense of invading your privacy.
"We're all trying to tell ourselves that it's not about spying, but about another way to reduce the chances of a tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the providers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they are put in someone's bag without their knowledge, but we have not yet encountered such cases."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," adds Pilin.
In their view, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns that if the child does not want to take him, he will simply throw him away.
"Even younger children show great creativity in intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid being controlled."
"Parents used to rely heavily on mobile phones, but they could be switched off as easily as the tracking device," says Bočková.
In his view, it was questionable whether such a device was really useful in the event of an attack.
"If it is a prepared kidnapping, the author will almost always check whether the child has any electronic device that can reveal his location."
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices is extended, it will also look for them, since their sale will undoubtedly be carried out with a lot of publicity."
"In such cases, criminals always go one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised attack by a paedophile.
According to Robert Čech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is destroyed immediately, its presence can help.
"You can configure the device to send the position regularly after a certain period."
"If you suffer damage, at least it will facilitate the last position of the person in question."
"The most expensive devices include a tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and stays motionless, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," says Čech.
In your opinion, such a service can be obtained even with smart phones with navigation, in which only special software should be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that for the time being they are devices with a size similar to a matchbox or smaller mobile phones.
So they can get lost.
According to Macro Weil's Pilin, for this reason tests are currently being carried out with devices that look like a digital clock.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a possible attacker may not identify the device."
"Or identify him after some time, which can make the police buy time," he adds.
Although the tracking devices are carried on the wrist or hanging, they will continue to use the same technology used for vehicle tracking.
This is the verification of the position with a GPS system (which is used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough wicks to surround the whole of Chechnya, but it only lasts two years.
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of wick to hold explosives.
Already last year the Ministry of Defence added 224 kilometers of wick to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the wick's useful life is two years, four at most.
The army bought the explosive wick from the STV Group, a.s. for forty million kroner.
The General's staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of wick by saying that soldiers need for training maneuvers 60 kilometers of wick a year.
According to the calculations of the army pyrotechnicians, with whom MF DNES was contacted, it is decided, however, that, in such a case, they should perform such maneuvers with frequent use of explosives every year also all generals, high-ranking officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
They did not want to exempt the Minister of Defense Alexandr Vondr and the captain of the Vlastimil Picek army.
Only then could it be justified for the army to spend sixty kilometres of wick.
This length is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if so, the army would have enough stocks for more than ten years.
If, on the contrary, as the experts say, for the initial training of each new professional arrives with a maximum of two meters of wick, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the Rapid Intervention Brigade complained to Minister Vondra recently because they say they have little ammunition for various weapons, so even shooting practices for money are limited.
And let's not talk about the lack of underwear.
"I also fail to understand that they repeatedly buy us such quantities of wick."
"But it's your decision, and they'll certainly know why they're acting like this."
"For us, the army is a good customer to whom, as a company, we try to satisfy," admits STV Group's commercial director, Jan Děcký.
The spokesman of the Ministry of Defence Jan Pejšek defends the hundreds of kilometers of wick by also saying that he will have stocks of this "munition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký, of STV Group, indicates that the wick only has a useful life of four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or police, of two years.
"If it is stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four," says one of the soldiers who, due to the possible criticisms of the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of their useful life, each ammunition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that by buying 445 kilometers of wick, he got a discount.
"They cost us 60% less than last year's order of 244 kilometers," says the spokesman Pejšek of the Ministry of Defence's shopping centre.
Just to compare: the annual wick consumption of police pyrotechnics, which eliminate World War II ammunition or left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 metres for years.
In addition, the police always ask only the fair amount to exhaust the ammunition before its useful life runs out.
They decided it for safety reasons for pyrotechnicians and, in the meantime, they can get more modern and reliable wick types.
The Ministry already has clear difficulties in finishing tens of thousands of tons of ammunition at the time of the Warsaw Pact, when the Czechoslovak army of two hundred thousand people were preparing for a campaign in the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years there will be the following problem with the current one: you will have to eliminate hundreds of kilometers of old wick, which is now being bought "barata".
