A survey that reveals ridiculous rules
The Absurdez survey of the year is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
You've already managed to eliminate some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurdez survey of the year was the obligation to bring to the administration documents to which officials can access online.
The decision was adopted by more than a third of almost 4,000 voters.
For example, the social security administration requested an extract from the business register, although its officials could obtain it with two movements of the mouse.
Thanks to the survey, this has changed.
"The Czech social security administration will no longer ask for an extract from the business register when it carries out a check on the taxes of the insured person," said ČSSZ spokesman Jana Buraňová.
The objective of the Absurdez survey of the year is to consult the rules and regulations that businesses and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic must respect and to try to eliminate those that are absurd.
This year it forms for the fourth time part of the business tournament of the Hospodářské noviny publication and begins to create hobby also among the general public.
While last year's edition counted with the participation of three thousand voters, this year it reached almost four thousand.
And it is not surprising, since we still have a number of legal obligations that must be respected simply to trade.
"Perhaps in number of papers needed for tax reporting we are in the world's first place," says Karel Havlíček of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
For years, the simplification of business rules has been a stated goal of all governments.
However, compared to the rest of the world, the situation of improvement especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, from the point of view of the conditions for having a company, the Czech Republic is in position 74a, i.e. eight positions worse than last year.
The Absurdez contest of the year was held for the first time in 2006 and is repeated every year in the same way.
Anyone can indicate some administrative or bureaucratic absurdity every year between April and the end of September, when the competition is closed.
Proposals can be made on the website www.firmaroku.cz. The contest organiser then selects seven candidates for the "anti-premium" and, during October, allows the public to vote on the Internet via www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
Wins the absurdity that receives the most votes.
For this year's survey, more than one hundred were presented, including 105 rules and regulations that make no sense.
The examples were sent by both employers, professional associations and journalists.
Among the "finalists" of the competition was, for example, the requirement that vehicles for the maintenance of roads and motorways pay the toll or that entrepreneurs with twenty employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
This year's list of seventy proposals is posted on the competition pages.
The announcement of the contest, which is always held at the beginning of November in the Wenceslas Square in Prague, is part of an event in which personalities from the political and social world often participate.
This year, for example, this event was attended by Eva Svobodová, director of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, or Petr Kužel, president of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic.
"Economic prosperity cannot be sustained if the state is constantly obstructing entrepreneurs, so my goal is to eliminate a minimum of thirty paragraphs every year that currently unnecessarily complicate trade," said Minister of Industry and Trade Martin Kocourek.
Efforts to eliminate absurd regulations are not left in drunkard water.
In 2007, what was most disturbing to people was the employer's obligation to communicate three days in advance to the business office of the permanent operating area, the intention to go with a post to a fair or exhibition.
This obligation was eliminated in the new industrial law.
The obligation that ended in second place in the number of votes in 2007, i.e. the communication to the work office by its foreign workers of work trips of up to 30 days, was eliminated in the law of the so-called green card.
And the third one is over.
The Absurdity of 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have in their consultation a large mirror, a refrigerator and two floor scales.
Therefore, this year the Ministry of Health issued a communication saying that it had eliminated the obligation to have a refrigerator.
