Regulated rents, which benefit residents of about 300,000 floors, could increase next year to 10%.
The young Czechs get drunk with Fernet and rum. The beer is no longer in shape, because it has a slow effect.
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause young drinkers under the age of fifteen to end up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome the hangover are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors who find themselves with such cases at the hospital's pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because it takes them a long time to get drunk."
"Fashion is now strong alcoholic beverages," says Právo, head of pediatrics at Hořovice Hospital in the center of Bohemia, Luděk Pelikán.
"When they get a bottle of ice cream from their father, it can be whisky, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
"Vodka has the advantage that it is lightened with juice and that it doesn't smell that much," he explains.
The spokesperson for the Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová, also confirms this.
"Normally, it's usually Fernet or rum."
"These are modern alcoholic beverages, especially among schoolchildren."
"In some cases, they use aperitif that they caught at home," Jurinová adds.
According to Chief Pelikán, 13- and 14-year-old drinkers usually appear in hospitals.
Before Hořovice, where he has worked since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to come in maybe four times."
"It started at the age of twelve when she was brought in with 3.5 alcohol in her blood, in addition to a mixture with ecstasy," says the department's doctor on this case.
"He was at the Holešovice fair at some dance party."
"The interesting thing is that his mother was not surprised that his daughter disappeared 48 hours," the boss is surprised.
It is precisely the lack of interest of the parents or even their clear tolerance for drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, one cannot speak of dependence itself.
"Alcohol means a person who has a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children."
"In those who repeatedly drink alcohol, it is rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment," explains Chief Pelikán.
According to the spokesperson Jurinová, forty drunken children were hospitalized until mid-November this year at the Motol Paediatric Clinic.
However, the statistics show only those who come with severe poisoning and must remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after walking medical examination, go home with parents or the police do not count.
In addition to the cases in which children simply meet after school and drink aguardiente, there are three seasonal ups and downs for Pelikán: the day of witches, the end of the year and the end of the school year.
"In such circumstances, they drink from bad notes or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holiday."
"On the day of the witches I have come to see up to seven drunken children in admissions at once," adds Pelikán.
Drinkers who spend the night in detox under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided by injecting a serum with glucose and by the nutrients missing from the body.
"These carry it much better, because after the agitated night, they get up well and they don't hurt anything."
"They are only confused about where they are," says Pelikán, adding that patients often lose their temper at least when they see the expenses they have generated.
Ambulance transfer and hospitalization in a room for serious patients cost about tens of thousands of crowns.
"I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when on the visit I tell them directly to the children how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a job for young people to earn enough to pay for themselves that night," adds Pelikán.
In his view, health insurance, perhaps as a retrogressive measure, which usually reimburses people for the costs of treatment, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
Two L-159 aircraft are found for the first time in the hands of others in Spain
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, by which the Czech Ministry of Defence replaced the Casa C-295M aircraft, left for Seville on Tuesday, where the manufacturer of the Casa - EADS aircraft is located.
This is the first time a device of this type has been in the hands of anyone other than the Czech army.
For the time being, they were only abroad for practice or demonstration flights.
It is the biplaza version L-159T1, which until now used the Czech army and was still in a state of flight.
The remaining three aircraft are the L-159 single-seat aircraft.
These are still kept in Aer Vodochody and the sales broker, Omnipol, already took care of them last week.
Jan Peješk of the Defense Press Department indicates that it is not yet known when the planes physically will be withdrawn from Vodochody.
"The L-159 single-seat aircraft, on the other hand, were separated from the aircraft repaired long ago, without any investments or additional contributions by the Ministry."
"The two-seat L-159T1 were exchanged in their current state," Právo Pejšek told.
He added that the army did not run out of two-seater aircraft, since in May 2009 the army signed a contract with Aer Vodochody for the construction of four unnecessary L-159 dual-seater devices.
One of the new aircraft was received by the army in July, the other will be delivered by the end of the year.
According to Pejšek, EADS committed to adding aircraft to the equipment of some allied countries.
"The contract clearly indicates that EADS is the company that withdraws L-159 aircraft and will serve as pilots for NATO countries."
"It is therefore up to the buyer to decide how to use them in this framework," Pejšek says.
The Hospodářské noviny newspaper published earlier that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
