The army already received three Casa planes and the last one should arrive at the Prague airport of Kbely in fourteen days.
A longer index finger than the annular indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have the longest rate than annular are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday in a British magazine on cancer.
They could depend on the testosterone level, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that the relative length of the finger can be a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, particularly for men up to the age of 60," said the co-author of Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
Therefore, the finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, particularly if this feature is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, as indicated by Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart of over 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the indica finger of the right hand shorter than the annular.
They had the same probabilities of prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were of the same length.
For men with a longer index than the annular finger, this risk was reduced by 33 per cent; for men under 60 per cent, the reduction was 87 per cent.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the womb.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knows the study, but that it does not seem to him that the relationship between the length of the fingers and cancer can be "showed completely".
