This is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German put on the market in 2007 for purposes far removed from the high car competition.
Called PLM, this powerful computer tool has been used to design assembly chains of manufacturing factories around the world, power plants, high precision instruments.
The objective is to reproduce, faithfully simulate the product or process before building it in a real way, thus avoiding avoidable failures and costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon's cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan's most famous utility cars.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of the Siemens industrial division, explains that the use of this computer instrument in his Formula 1 factory has allowed Red Bull to design and carry out "in a few hours, almost in real time", the modifications, changes and improvements that are detected during the races and in the trials.
Russwurm explains that the squids in 1992 had an average of 10 technicians on their team who were able to make a maximum of three or four improvements to the vehicles during each season.
The Red Bull team now employs 180 young high-skilled professionals who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyze and project all sorts of changes in the bolides.
Siemens manager explained that PLM software is able to analyze and improve all elements of Red Bull bolidos with the exception of the engine, which is Renault's entire responsibility.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
The changes can be brought from virtual reality from simulator to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
As the only limitation of this insanity of technological improvement is the amount of $40 million that each Formula 1 team can spend at most every season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to design and produce its bolides in a locality about 50 kilometres from London.
These are two buildings where visits are restricted, especially for journalists.
Everything that happens there is considered "high secret."
The staff for this task is 580 people, including his two pilots, Champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
