Shoemaker and the German Red Line
Berlin has chosen to remain in the euro, but has set the conditions for the whole Union.
Tensions in the markets have led to a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has advanced new measures of adjustment, from tax reductions to SMEs, regulation of private agencies of placement or suppression of the 426 euros of assistance to unemployed without benefit, until the privatization of 49% of AENA, of the management of the airports of Barajas and El Prat and of 30% of Lotteries of the State.
On the other hand, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, has joined the criticisms of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility to unleash the current crisis.
How do you interpret these movements?
Go forward that Merkel's position is not a mistake in his communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another twist in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of many of its partners.
Faced with European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible exits to the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, while the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the framework, even though it now seems science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigour, fines to violating countries, possible suspension of payments from any of them and extension of the costs of potential adjustments to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there is no excuse.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government took a constitutional reform out of hand to prevent them from starting in 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be done (plans of fiscal rigour and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The second on the front was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully extended Greece's rescue decision.
Already then it was fiercely criticized, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public and published opinion were very much against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, again Merkel emerges with a clear position, demanding the reform of the Union's treaties, in order to make possible the rescue of a country and, at the same time, to force private lenders to run at a part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But its proposal, although somewhat sweet, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should be attending the process of reforming the Union that will enable those measures to take place from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which he may not agree very much, from that date on the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary area, in which the offending countries will be severely punished, may be forced to declare themselves in default of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also incur part of the cost.
Germany is pointing out that we must follow a severe path of growth with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, productivity improvements and competitiveness and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, such as the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, simply won't tolerate it.
The invitation is clear.
And it would be wrong not to understand.
It is not just a question of bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What they demand of us is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do in these circumstances is fool ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give way to greater peace of mind.
And let us take advantage of the window of opportunity that we have been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood this and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday's meeting with the big companies and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite the criticisms of Merkel, the thesis that we have to put order at home has opened up.
But the red line that Germany has drawn there is, and it doesn't look like they're going to move it.
And, among the possibilities envisaged, the possibility of leaving a monetary zone too crowded with unscrupulous countries, cannot be excluded.
Then Germany will always be able to tell us that it had already warned us.
Sport and law enforcement fraud
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos before the Ajax prove witty but unwilling to escape a sanction.
The alleged expulsion by two players from Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match held on 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether such behavior is anti-sport and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the game (which his team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately wasted time in taking out faulty paths to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
That way, and since Real Madrid will end up as leader of its group, both players will meet the regulatory penalty the next game of the bass, against the Auxerre, and will be able to pass clean cards to the next stage.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee has sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two matches, and the players involved with different economic amounts.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the rules not written, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the reported case is due to the fact that he has been starred by a team of the Real Madrid entity (who in his anthem presumes of nobility and honor, and who in past times has fined his players for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether such behaviour is not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether such actions involve the commission of legal fraud; they are, in fact, actions which are respectful of the sports regulation, but seem to circumvent its meaning.
The question goes on to examine the type of damage they cause to the sports spirit.
One of the assets that understands the sports spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not put in jeopardy, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with the clean game is to prevent the team of the infringing players from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which did not happen either.
However, the paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it was not suited to what we normally characterized as a trap or fraud of law, because its violation of the rules was not made in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but rather that its action tried to be the most obvious to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage offenders gain from the intentional misdemeanours examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the rival is not put in a disadvantageous position and profit is not obtained in the same game, because obviously the result of the action means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club won't be able to count on those players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will begin the next phase of the League of Champions without cards that may threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminateness, as the team can be eliminated from the first of the changes, and also with this performance the players fulfill a penalty game and pass to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards is produced with a less than in the first cycle.
So, if you go through rounds, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions do not run counter to the sporting spirit, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that will benefit the most from what the rules allow.
In the assumption that we are occupied, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without bypassing the punishment or running away from it.
Although the border between ingenuity and law enforcement fraud is diffuse, on this occasion I believe it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I think, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and the way in which the directive was transmitted to provoke them.
The damage to the principles of sport caused by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
